text:
Sydney model saves teens who fell through frozen Central Park pond in New York while taking selfies February 21, 2017 11:56pm Image Australian helps rescue teens from frozen Central Park pond 0:33 
Australian Ethan Turnbull helped rescue a group of teens who fell through the ice at Central Park pond while trying to take a selfie. Courtesy: NBC February 21st 2017 an hour ago /video/video.news.com.au/News/ Sydney model Ethan Turnbull, 24, helped to rescue a group of teens who fell through the ice at a pond in New York’s Central Park. Picture: Instagram/Ethan Turnbull Staff writers News Corp Australia Network Share Share on Twitter 
AN Australian male model has been hailed a hero after helping rescue a group of teens who fell through an ice-covered pond in New York’s Central Park. 
Ethan Turnbull, 24, was skateboarding with his friend, 23-year-old Bennett Jonas, when he saw the teens flailing in the icy water just before 6pm on Monday (11pm Monday AEDT). 
As Mr Jonas, also a male model, jumped into the pond, Mr Turnbull stood by to grab the teens. 
“The last two at the end, the kid at the end was unconscious,” Mr Turnbull, from Sydney, told NBC News . 
“[Mr Jonas] got him out, he was kind of out of breath, and [Jonas] threw him to me. I just kind of minded him until he came to.” A post shared by E T H A N. T. ™ (@ethanturnbull) on Feb 20, 2017 at 8:47pm PST 
Mr Jonas, from California man,he was swarmed by the terrified kids, who were screaming out for help, when he jumped into the frigid lake. 
“The only thing you could see was the back zipper of his backpack,” he recalled. “I grabbed his backpack not knowing if there was a body on it.” A post shared by E T H A N. T. ™ (@ethanturnbull) on Oct 26, 2016 at 10:10pm PDT A post shared by E T H A N. T. ™ (@ethanturnbull) on Aug 15, 2016 at 2:08am PDT 
The Good Samaritans helped pull four of the seven teenage boys, ages 15 to 16, from the frozen pond. 
The boys were rushed to a local hospital where they were treated for minor hypothermia Ethan Turnbull, 24, said he was in the right place at the right time. Picture: NBC Source: Supplied 
Fire Department of New York Deputy Chief John Scof said the teens had been horsing around on the thin ice before it gave way. 
“They were just being kids,” he explained during a press conference, according to The New York Post . 
“I think after tonight we can reinforce to the people that playing on ice is not a good idea. [The teens] are all okay. They are suffering from some mild hypothermia.” 
He said most of the pond was covered by a solid seven-centimetre layer of ice, but “not thick enough to hold them up”. The teens had to be rescued after falling through the ice into the off-limits pond. Picture: AP Photo/Kathy Willens Source: AP The teens didn’t heed a sign near the pond that warned, “Danger Thin Ice Keep Off.” Picture: AP Photo/Kathy Willens Source: AP 
Following the heroic rescue, Mr Turnbull wrote on Instagram: “‘Right place right time’— Fortunate enough to have been in the position to help multiple younger generation New Yorkers today. 
“With out the help of my Buddy @bennett_jonas the outcome of this event would have been much different. Thanks to all the friends and family that have checked in.” A post shared by @bennett_jonas on Feb 20, 2017 at 8:39pm PST
